{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513577"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:11:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:11:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12162"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12162"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.12,0.09,0.04,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106386"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4692"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12162"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88839"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"337"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4979"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11639"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43296"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106386"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man with bony metastases from prostate cancer is referred to the palliative care service for for end-of-life care. He has recently been struggling with his daily activities due to pain and has been admitted under the general medical team in hospital. He has new onset severe pain in his lower back, which prevents him from walking more than five metres and corresponds well with radiologically-identified metastases. He also has ongoing fatigue and pelvic discomfort, related to metastatic lymph node involvement but his pain does not have any neuropathic features. He has tried paracetamol with minimal effect and up until now he has not been on any regular medication for his pain. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes and peptic ulcer disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line analgesic option?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fentanyl patch 25microg/hr transdermal weekly","Hydromorphone 4mg subcut 2hrly PRN","Ibuprofen 400mg oral three times daily","Piroxicam 20mg oral once daily","Morphine 2-5mg oral 2hrly PRN"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMorphine\u003C/strong\u003E is a first-line medication for analgesia to treat cancer-pain in opioid-na\u00efve patients. The morphine dose can be titrated on a PRN basis. It is a potent opioid analgesic used for the management of moderate to severe pain. It is the gold standard in palliative care, providing effective and safe pain relief. Furthermore, opioids are generally started on a PRN basis, which can then be used to calculate a sustained-release dose if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA fentanyl patch\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate first-line choice in this case, as it is usually reserved for patients who have developed tolerance to other opioid analgesics or who have difficulty taking medications orally. A fentanyl patch is difficult to titrate the dose - morphine allows for more gradual dose titration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous hydromorphone\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate first-line choice in this case, as it is usually reserved for patients who have developed tolerance to other opioid analgesics. The dose is far too high to be given initially to an opioid-naive patient (equating to a total daily oral morphine equivalent of approximately 240-360mg) as this drug is 5-7.5x stronger than morphine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIbuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) used for the management of mild to moderate pain, fever, and inflammation. However, it is not an appropriate choice for severe cancer related pain. Moreover, it can cause gastrointestinal bleeding and renal dysfunction, particularly in elderly patients with comorbidities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPiroxicam\u003C/strong\u003E is also an NSAID used for the management of mild to moderate pain and inflammation, and would be inappropriate for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Morphine is a first line opioid in palliative care and should be started at the lowest tolerated oral dose, where possible.","Hydromorphone is 5-7.5x stronger than oral morphine"],"references":["Wiffen PJ, Wee B, Moore RA (2013) Oral morphine for cancer pain. Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews issue 7: CD003868. Available from: https://www.cochranelibrary.com/cdsr/doi/10.1002/14651858.CD003868/full","Yoong J, Poon P. Principles of cancer pain management: An overview and focus on pharmacological and interventional strategies. Aust J Gen Pract. 2018;47(11):758-762. doi:10.31128/AJGP-07-18-4629. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/november/principles-of-cancer-pain-management"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88839"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12162"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88839"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-19T13:15:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T13:17:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4692"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106386"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,